Research Ideas
Investigate alternative one‑class models: Isolation Forest, Deep SVDD (Deep One‑Class Classification), or autoencoders if more data becomes available.

Explore temporal fusion: Instead of aggregating windowed features by simple statistics, consider using a sequence model (e.g., 1D CNN or LSTM) on the windowed feature sequences to capture temporal dynamics more directly. This would require a significantly larger dataset.

Active learning for impostor detection: Use the confidence scores of the OCSVM to selectively request labels for ambiguous sessions, gradually improving the model in deployment.

Device‑invariant features: Test whether features normalised by device‑specific characteristics (screen size, sensor range) generalise across different phone models.

Explainability: Use SHAP values on the final OCSVM (via kernel SHAP or similar) to explain individual predictions to users or auditors.

Deployment Plans
Model export: The current pipeline already saves {user}_ocsvm.pkl and {user}_scaler.pkl using joblib. These can be loaded in a lightweight inference service.

Feature extraction on‑device: The SessionLevelFeatureExtractor logic can be ported to Java/Kotlin (Android) or Swift (iOS) to extract features directly on the mobile device, sending only the feature vector to the authentication server.

Real‑time scoring: The server loads the user‑specific model and scaler, scales the incoming feature vector, and returns decision_function score. If the score ≥ threshold, the transaction is allowed.

Model update: New genuine sessions can be added to the user’s training set periodically, and the model retrained (or updated via incremental SVM if available).

Threshold adjustment: The system can expose a configuration parameter to adjust the threshold based on risk appetite (lower threshold → more security but higher FRR).

